Aux:TextAnnotations.Aux:document_text: The community is home to the University of Evansville, the University of Southern Indiana and Ivy Tech Community College. Major industries include manufacturing, warehousing and distribution, retailing, health care, and finance and business services. Corporate headquarters include Accuride, Atlas World Group, Berry Plastics, Old National Bank, Shoe Carnival and Vectren. Major manufacturing operations in nearby rural towns include AK Steel in Rockport, Alcoa in Newburgh, SABIC in Mt. Vernon and Toyota in Princeton. Evansville has emerged as the tri-state's major center for the health care and medical sciences industries. Deaconess Hospital and St. Mary's Medical Center, along with the Deaconess Gateway and Women's Hospital located just outside of city limits, provide the anchors for a vast health care system that is among the region's largest employers. The 2010 Census indicated that the population of Evansville was 117,429. The median household income was $35,469. 19.5% of Evansville residents live in poverty. 54.9% of public school children in Vanderburgh County receive free or reduced price lunches. The largest racial/ethinic groups are White (80.9%) followed by Black (12.5%) and Hispanic (2.6%). The median age is 36.5 years. As of December, 2012, the unemployment rate was 7.3%, compared to the Indiana unemployment rate of 8.2%
